'''Harragas''' (from [[Arabic language|Arabic]] حراقة, ''ḥarrāga, ḥarrāg'', "those who burn" (the frontier)) are [[North Africa]]n migrants who attempt to [[illegal immigration|illegally immigrate]] to [[Europe]] or to European-controlled islands in makeshift boats.<ref name="wiki">[[:fr:Harraga]], Retrieved 10 February 2011{{Better source|reason=per WP:CIRCULAR|date=August 2015}}</ref> The word Harraga (in ar: حراقة), is from Algerian Arabic, designating "those who burn.", meaning those who burn their ID-papers and seek their fortune as asylumseekers in Europe. The Harrga is the action of "burning the borders and the sea."

On the Mediterranean coast of North Africa, Algerian, Tunisian, and Moroccan harragas typically hope to cross the [[Strait of Gibraltar]] in order to reach Spain, specifically the Spanish regions of [[Andalusia]], [[Ceuta]]<ref name="wiki"/> and [[Melilla]].<ref name="wiki"/> Additionally, harragas also sometimes manage to complete the voyage from Africa to the island nation of [[Malta]],<ref name=Magreb>{{cite web |url=http://www.magharebia.com/cocoon/awi/xhtml1/en_GB/features/awi/newsbriefs/general/2009/02/02/newsbrief-03 |title=Maghreb nationals among harragas caught in Malta  |author= |date=2009-02-02 |work= |publisher=United States Africa Command |accessdate=10 February 2011}}</ref> or the Italian island of [[Lampedusa]].<ref name="wiki"/> From here they often go on to emigrate to other regions of Europe.<ref name=Magreb/>

On the Atlantic coast of North Africa, Mauritanian and Senegalese harragas set off in hope of reaching the Spanish-controlled [[Canary Islands]] in small, flat-bottomed boats referred to in Spanish as "patera",<ref name="patera">[[:es:Patera]], Retrieved 10 February 2011{{Better source|reason=per WP:CIRCULAR|date=August 2015}}</ref> or in rigid or inflatable rafts, (such as [[Zodiac Marine & Pool|"Zodiac"]] rafts),<ref name="patera"/> or even [[Pedalo|paddle boats]].<ref name="patera"/> Obviously, boats such as these are not designed for ocean crossings and the death rates for harragas are very high. The motivations for undertaking this extremely risky act are twofold: profound economic poverty and extreme political repression, both widespread throughout North Africa.<ref name="wiki"/>

==Film==
{{update section|date=December 2015}}
Algerian film director {{ill|Moussa Haddad|fr|Moussa Haddad|vertical-align=sup}} started shooting a film entitled ''Harraga Blues'' February 6, 2011.<ref name=HarragaBlues>{{cite web |url=http://www.elmoudjahid.com/en/flash-actu/597# |title= Movie: Director Moussa Haddad starts shooting ''Harraga Blues'' |date= |work=06-02-2011 |publisher=El Moujahid |accessdate=10 February 2011}}</ref> The project is currently still in production.<ref name=HarragaBlues/>

