{{Infobox writer | name = Inger Edelfeldt | image = I-edelfeldt-3.jpeg | caption = Inger Edelfeldt at the [[Gothenburg Book Fair]] in 2014 | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1956|07|14}} | birth_place = [[Stockholm]], Sweden | birth_name = | death_date = | death_place = | occupation = {{hlist|Author|Illustrator|Translator|Comic book creator}} | nationality = Swedish | language = Swedish | notableworks = ''Duktig pojke'' ("Good Boy") | spouse = | children = | awards = | years_active = 1977– | signature = | website = {{URL|http://edelfeldt.blogspot.se/}} }}
'''Inger Edelfeldt''' (born 14{{nbsp}}July 1956) is a Swedish [[author]], [[illustrator]] and translator.
== Personal life == Edelfeldt was born in [[Stockholm]] in 1956. Her father was an engineer and her mother was a house wife. Her father user to tell her stories before he went to work in the mornings, but he also suffered from depressions and was treated with [[electrotherapy]]. The situation at home reflected on the young Edelfeldt, she was bullied at school and suffered from self-harming [[Obsessive–compulsive disorder|OCD]]. As an adult she tried several therapies and finally settled on Zen coaching and meditation.<ref name=dn>{{cite web|last1=Johansson|first1=Astrid|title=Den litterära kameleonten har blivit zen-coach|trans-title=The literary chameleon has become a zen-coach|url=http://www.dn.se/livsstil/intervjuer/den-litterara-kameleonten-har-blivit-zen-coach/|website=www.dn.se|date=3 January 2010|publisher=[[Dagens Nyheter]]|accessdate=19 September 2015}}</ref>
== Career == Edelfeldt made her debut in 1977 with the book ''Duktig pojke'' ("Good Boy").<ref name=NE>{{cite web|last1=Johannesson,|first1=Hans-Erik|last2=Littberger Caisou-Rousseau|first2=Inger|title=Inger Edelfeldt|url=http://www.ne.se/uppslagsverk/encyklopedi/lång/inger-edelfeldt|website=www.ne.se|publisher=[[Nationalencyklopedin]]|accessdate=18 September 2015}}</ref> The novel is about the boy Jim who is lonely and asserts himself by excelling in school. The book was later reworked into a [[young adult fiction|book for young adults]] and it is regarded as one of the first [[coming out]] novels in Sweden.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Nordenstam|first1=Anna|title=Recensioner av doktorsavhandlingar|trans-title=Reviews of PhD theses|journal=Samlaren|date=2010|issue=131|page=421|url=http://uu.diva-portal.org/smash/get/diva2:439022/FULLTEXT01.pdf|accessdate=19 September 2015}}</ref> She has written more than 30 books since then,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Qvarnström|first1=Niklas|title=Dödens negativ|trans-title=Negative of death|url=http://www.sydsvenskan.se/kultur--nojen/dodens-negativ/|website=www.sydsvenskan.se|date=27 January 2014|publisher=[[Sydsvenskan]]|accessdate=19 September 2015}}</ref> most of which are novels, short stories, poetry books, comic books and books for children and young people.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.worldcat.org/search?q=Inger+Edelfeldt&dblist=638&fq=ap%3A%22edelfeldt%2C+inger%22&qt=facet_ap%3A|title=Inger Edelfeldt |accessdate= 28 March 2010|publisher=WorldCat.org}}</ref> Edelfeldt's young adult novels often revolves around subjects like identity and efforts of liberation.<ref name="NE" /> Another common theme is mans double nature, the mirror image and the dark side of a good life.<ref name=litteratur /> She writes in a multitude of styles such as satire, fable, drama and has been described as easy to read with a special sense of humor.<ref name=nordic />
{{quote|"[Edelfeldt]...is a crossbreed between [[Astrid Lindgren]] and [[Franz Kafka]]."|Göran Hägg, docent in literary science<ref name=litteratur />}}
Edelfeldt is a self-taught artist and she says that she has been inspired by the works of [[Leonardo da Vinci]], [[Arthur Rackham]] and [[Maurice Sendak]].{{citation needed|date=September 2015}} She has worked as an illustrator since 1976. She made [[Watercolor painting|aquarelles]] for the 1985 edition of the Tolkien calendar in the United States and the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sagan om ringen av Inger Edelfeldt|url=http://www.seriegalleriet.se/main.php?exhibit=110|website=www.seriegalleriet.se|publisher=Seriegalleriet|accessdate=19 September 2015}}</ref>
== In other media == In 1995, the [[Sveriges Television|Swedish television]] the TV-series ''Nattens barn'' (''"The Children of the night"''),<ref>{{cite web|title=Nattens barn|url=http://www.oppetarkiv.se/video/1560606/nattens-barn-avsnitt-1-av-4|website=www.oppetarkiv.se|publisher=[[Sveriges Television]]|accessdate=19 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150223230313/http://www.oppetarkiv.se/video/1560606/nattens-barn-avsnitt-1-av-4|archive-date=2015-02-23|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref> made after Edelfeldt's young adult novel ''Julliane och jag'' (''"Juliane and me"''). The series was directed by [[Lisa Ohlin]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Nattens barn|url=http://www.sfi.se/sv/svensk-filmdatabas/Item/?itemid=21904&type=MOVIE&iv=PdfGen|website=www.sfi.se|publisher=[[Swedish Film Institute]]|accessdate=19 September 2015}}</ref>
On 30{{nbsp}}July 1990, Edelfeldt hosted the noted radio program ''[[Sommar (radio program)|Sommar I P1]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Sommar- och Vintervärdar, 1959–2015|trans-title=Summer and Winter hosts, 1959–2015|url=https://sverigesradio.se/diverse/appdata/isidor/files/2071/14984.pdf|website=www.sverigesradio.se|page=10|publisher=[[Sveriges Radio]]}}</ref>
